text_display: I slept in my Model S for 8 days for a 2,400 mile road trip from California to New Mexico and back.  $0 hotel bills, $0 gas cost with free supercharging.  After two days of getting adjusted to it, I preferred it over the "check in, check out" of hotels.  I found that if you plug the car in first, then turn on the climate control, a Level 2 charger will power the heater for the whole night.  You don't get a reduction in range in the morning by using the heat if you do it this way.

text_display:
I stopped using Camp Mode to get rid of the fire video. It's cute for about ten minutes. I just drove across the U.S. and back again, coast to coast. First night I slept in my Model Y. I'd done that several times and liked it. The next night I stayed in a hotel, didn't cost much - was very nice. So next night I did it again, same chain. But this place was run down. It's more of a hassle to stay in a hotel, then it is to just park and climb in the back. After that I just slept in my car, unless I wanted to shower. It's a no brainer, pull into a rest stop, park. I have a 4" thick memory foam mattress, a sleeping bag, a regular pillow and a sleeping bag liner (that's the main thing I sleep in. Usually I just drape the sleeping bag over me. Black t-shirt over my eyes I can sleep right below a street light. I've slept in the car in freezing temps and when it's been very hot. I set the climate at 69¬∞ f which seems perfect. I think using just Climate will turn off after about 6 hours - usually makes no difference. If it does you just turn it on again with your phone. Great car. So some days I'd basically spend almost all the 24 hours in my Tesla. Stealth camping? Van people seem to eliminate all the windows. I don't cover any of the windows. One good trick is to park right next to the Supercharger. No one notices.
In Los Angeles when smoke from the wildfires blows in, I've found that my home HEPA filters can't keep up with it, so I just go out and sleep in my Tesla - I don't even have the upgrade Bio Warfare filters - but I'm going to get them. (I've camped like this in a Honda Odyssey, Prius V and all over the world in a lot of tents, rainflys and even just a bivy sack (10,000 foot mountain in Japan, blowing rain -- best night of my life.) Hope this helps. Enjoy your life.

text_display:
Most people completely missed why this is important. This is all for automation, and is not meant to replace cable charging for those of us at home. Most car owners would rather pay less in electricity and just walk 5 steps to plug in their cars every day. The presence wireless charging solution simply means that they're this much closer to having a fully automated taxi fleet.

For those who argue that robot arms can do it too, remember that just because you can, doesn't mean you should spend extra money on things that require more maintenance. There will be cleaning stations hubs, but charging pads will be scattered throughout many more locations.

Lastly, for those who assume it's inefficient, Tesla bought a company who claims to have an over 90% efficient charging system. This ain't your smartphone Qi charging standard.
text_original:
Most people completely missed why this is important.  This is all for automation, and is not meant to replace cable charging for those of us at home.  Most car owners would rather pay less in electricity and just walk 5 steps to plug in their cars every day.  The presence wireless charging solution simply means that they're this much closer to having a fully automated taxi fleet.

For those who argue that robot arms can do it too, remember that just because you can, doesn't mean you should spend extra money on things that require more maintenance.  There will be cleaning stations hubs, but charging pads will be scattered throughout many more locations.

Lastly, for those who assume it's inefficient, Tesla bought a company who claims to have an over 90% efficient charging system.  This ain't your smartphone Qi charging standard.

The cybertruck doesn't have a gear transmission, meaning all of its power is in one gear. But the fact that the cybertruck was pulling another Porsche is because of its towing capacity, but on a normal road that wouldnt be the case. Because of the tow hitch not being connected to a steel frame, if the truck hits a pothole then the back bumper will shear completely off. This is often the outcome when hauling a light tralier on a bumpy road at high speeds.
Basiclly Tesla need some improvement in the truck, but so far its offroad baja performence is second to none.

text_display: I'm interested to know how the load stresses from the pillars are transferred to whatever the structural member is called that runs along the center of the roof line. I remember lots of cars from the 80s with t-tops that would constantly get tweaked, preventing you from removing or reinstalling the T-tops. Camaros were famous for this. That and leaking. The car would literally begin sagging in the middle, thus closing the Gap in the roof preventing removal or installation of T-tops. There was also a problem with these cars having windshield cracks that would start at the top of the a-pillar. Something about the load needing to be transferred to the center brace in the roof cause cracking in the windshield. I would love a little tiny bit of engineering detail on how Tesla braced the chassis to prevent this phenomenon that is so well known to us in the automotive industry. Other questions include, was there a weight savings or cost with this design. Also, how much does the door protrude out from the side of the vehicle? What is the overall width of the vehicle with both doors open to their widest point?
text_original: I'm interested to know how the load stresses from the pillars are transferred to whatever the structural member is called that runs along the center of the roof line. I remember lots of cars from the 80s with t-tops that would constantly get tweaked, preventing you from removing or reinstalling the T-tops. Camaros were famous for this. That and leaking. The car would literally begin sagging in the middle, thus closing the Gap in the roof preventing removal or installation of T-tops. There was also a problem with these cars having windshield cracks that would start at the top of the a-pillar. Something about the load needing to be transferred to the center brace in the roof cause cracking in the windshield. I would love a little tiny bit of engineering detail on how Tesla braced the chassis to prevent this phenomenon that is so well known to us in the automotive industry. Other questions include, was there a weight savings or cost with this design. Also, how much does the door protrude out from the side of the vehicle? What is the overall width of the vehicle with both doors open to their widest point?

I live in the mountains of Colorado, and have a Model Y Long Range‚Ä¶I take this thing EVERYWHERE. In the first year I put over 23,000 miles on it, taking road trips to the Texas coast and up to Montana. It drives beautifully in the mountains‚Ä¶regenerative braking makes the car even more efficient when going downhill. I‚Äôll run around, plug it in at night, and charge for $1-2.00. A 160 mile round trip down the mountain for errands might cost $6-7. My trips to Austin cost $75, while our 4Runner is around $224 ($260 at the highest gas price). I will NEVER buy another gas car again‚Ä¶the direct buying process was the least stressful experience I‚Äôve ever had buying a car‚Ä¶no fighting with commissioned salespeople and finance managers. It was magical. ‚ù§

The supercharger network gives Tesla a HUGE advantage over other EVs. I keep the Tesla mobile travel kit in my car with RV plugs just in case, but I‚Äôve never used Chargepoint or the overly-complicated third-party networks. I just pull up, charge, and I‚Äôm on my way. My friend with the Mustang Mach-E is afraid to take it anywhere because she has no idea how to charge it on the road. In 14 months I‚Äôve never come across a broken charger‚Ä¶you don‚Äôt have that same sophisticated charging experience with the others. Even our plug is elegantly small‚Ä¶I understand the weight and cumbersome size of the other charger plugs can cause faults in charging. Way to go, Tesla. I love my car‚Ä¶

text_display:
(Model Y driver here; so largely a Tesla fan.) This is a great illustration, and it looks really cool, but I‚Äôd have to experiment with it before I‚Äôm convinced that a high and variable steering ratio has actual value. Two reasons:

First, parking and U-turns require not only a tight turning radius, but also detailed precision control of the turning radius. Small movements of the steering wheel making large changes in the turning radius makes that high-precision more difficult to attain.

Second, what problem does a high steering ratio solve? I can‚Äôt recall ever having heard of accidents because of a low steering ratio‚Ä¶? That is, it‚Äôs really cool technology, but does it actually improve anything?

Now, no such question about the 4-wheel-steering part. That is almost certainly a huge win!
text_original:
(Model Y driver here;  so largely a Tesla fan.)  This is a great illustration, and it looks really cool, but I‚Äôd have to experiment with it before I‚Äôm convinced that a high and variable steering ratio has actual value.  Two reasons:

First, parking and U-turns require not only a tight turning radius, but also _detailed precision control_ of the turning radius.  Small movements of the steering wheel making large changes in the turning radius makes that high-precision more difficult to attain.

Second, what _problem_ does a high steering ratio solve?  I can‚Äôt recall ever having heard of accidents because of a low steering ratio‚Ä¶?  That is, it‚Äôs really cool technology, but does it actually improve anything?

Now, no such question about the 4-wheel-steering part.  That is _almost certainly_ a huge win!

text_display:
How to make a Bacon and Omellete Grilled Cheese Sandwich

Omelette. Take 3 Organic Pete and Gerry eggs and mix them with a small amount of milk. Then, put the mixture into a 10 inch round frying pan. Put the lid of the frying pan on and set the heat to 5/med. Wait until the mixture is fully cooked (no raw/wet spots whatsoever). Now, put a reasonable amount of cheddar cheese onto the cooked egg mixture. You can also put bacon with the cheese if that‚Äôs what you prefer. After, fold the omelette once (it should look like a semicircle). Now, take the omelette out of the pan for now.
Grilled Cheese. Take two slices of Publix Brioche bread and spread some lightly salted butter or mayo on one side of each slice of bread. Then put a slice of Vermont cheddar cheese on the opposite sides of the bread slices. Put the omelette in between the bread slices (the butter and cheese should be connected to the bread during this process. Now, put this sandwich onto the same pan. Cook each side to your liking, whether it‚Äôs perfectly cooked or not. After you are done cooking it, cut it down the middle so that there are to triangle slices of grilled cheese.
Enjoy

text_display: This is probably the best EV for the money. One thing that Elon needs to invent is computer-controlled battery cubes rated at 5 KWh rather than the standard 60,80,100, and 120 KWh configurations. That way, they can be sold as individual units to manufacturers who want smaller vehicles with shorter range or in hybrid or PEHV configurations.  There would be thousands of applications for those computer-controlled "cube" batteries. They can be wired in parallel to power a small car, large auto, pickup, or SUV, golf cart, riding mower, push mower, backpack blower, etc. But of course, being computer-controlled when they are at the end of life, the small cubes can just be replaced.  No need to spend thousands to replace the entire battery, just replace the ones needed for a few hundred bucks. DIYers would be able to do that themselves. In most cases, when the battery fails, it is usually component failure, not failure of the entire battery. This will make the battery-powered objects more desirable, cheaper to buy and maintain, and FAR less fire-prone.

text_display:
As a day #1 reservation holder with a ready-to-configure order, and a huge fan of the Tesla mission of transition to clean electric transportation, I'd like to propose some constructive feedback regarding the key card...

For those of us who's cell phone runs out of battery, becomes stolen, gets dropped and Bluetooth inadvertently disabled or damaged, locks due to an over the air apple software update, who's toddler decides to hide daddy's phone (or worse yet drop it in the toilet), for folks who leave their phone in their car while working out, going to the beach, pool, and other non-friendly cell phone environments, for flip phone users, or for those of us who enjoy getting away from the yoke of continual streams of text messages and Internet connectedness and just plain don't carry a smart phone around with them 24/7, I propose the following question:

Do you think that after in such enumerated circumstances it is practical, and most importantly safe, for my wife or daughter to have to fumble through her purse at night in a dark parking lot while standing next to her Model 3 searching for her wallet, opening and flashing it to potential thieves and criminals, pulling out the key card, and gliding it around the B-pillar waiting for the car to detect the RFID signal and unlock? Can you see how this is dangerous? Adding a traditional remote keyless system with smart approach, like most traditional vehicles, would enable the vehicle to be ready for entry when the owner approaches the door and be much safer for those instances where communication with the driver's cell phone is inoperable or not present. Thanks and keep up the hard work!
